<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="27" type="bionomics">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Bionomics.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="27">
Specimens have been collected from clear cut areas, transitional zone of a coniferous forest, seepages, and river and creek edges, from moss, leaf litter, gravel, dung, carrion and pitfall traps (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-36174-7" author="Klimaszewski, J" journalOrPublisher="Springer, Cham" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" refId="B41" refString="Klimaszewski, J, Hoebeke, ER, Godin, B, Davies, A, Perry, KI, Bourdon, C, Winchester, N, 2020. Aleocharine rove beetles of British Columbia: a hotspot of Canadian biodiversity (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). Springer, Cham, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-36174-7" title="Aleocharine rove beetles of British Columbia: a hotspot of Canadian biodiversity (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-36174-7" year="2020">Klimaszewski et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="27" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="27">
<taxonomicName authority="Mulsant &amp; Rey, 1873" authorityName=", sensu nov." authorityYear="1873" baseAuthorityName="Maeklin" baseAuthorityYear="1852" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Philhygra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Philhygra laevicollis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laevicollis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Philhygra laevicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a western Nearctic species that was previously considered to include eastern populations that we here treat as 
<taxonomicName authority="Mulsant &amp; Rey, 1873" authorityName="Klimaszewski, Brunke &amp; Pentinsaari" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Philhygra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Philhygra pseudolaevicollis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudolaevicollis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Philhygra pseudolaevicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. that differs in male genitalia but also by the divergent DNA barcode sequence.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="27">
Neither this species nor 
<taxonomicName family="Staphylinidae" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. laevicollis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" rank="species" species="laevicollis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">P. laevicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are known from MB, this error was corrected by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-36174-7" author="Klimaszewski, J" journalOrPublisher="Springer, Cham" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" refId="B41" refString="Klimaszewski, J, Hoebeke, ER, Godin, B, Davies, A, Perry, KI, Bourdon, C, Winchester, N, 2020. Aleocharine rove beetles of British Columbia: a hotspot of Canadian biodiversity (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). Springer, Cham, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-36174-7" title="Aleocharine rove beetles of British Columbia: a hotspot of Canadian biodiversity (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-36174-7" year="2020">Klimaszewski et al. (2020)</bibRefCitation>
. We have observed some variation in the shape of the sclerotized structure present on the female pygidium between specimens collected in BC, but it is not yet clear whether additional species are overlooked within the present concept of 
<taxonomicName family="Staphylinidae" genus="P." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. laevicollis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" rank="species" species="laevicollis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">P. laevicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
